="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-types-of-sequins/">Sequins Decoration <span>(11)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="105"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-marking-the-borders-of-the-decoration/">Casual Garment Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="106"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/epaulettes-function-and-materials/">Epaulettes <span>(8)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="127"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tambour-or-luneville-embroidery-part-1/">Tambour or Luneville Embroidery <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="128"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/the-button-loop-closure-part-1/">The Button Loop Closure <span>(2)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#4289">Fancy Dresses for Girls  <span>(5)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="118"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/childrens-body-proportions/">The Law of Proportions in Children's Wear <span>(3)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="117"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-style-for-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 3 Years Old Girl <span>(9)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="119"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-dress/">Fancy Dress for 6 Years Old Girl <span>(16)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="120"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-style-with-respect-to-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 9 Years Old Girl <span>(14)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="135"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-dress-with-regard-to-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 12 Years Old Girl <span>(14)</span></a></li></ul></li>		</ul></div></div>													<div class="lesson-tab" role="tabpanel">				  <!-- Nav tabs -->				  <ul class="nav nav-tabs" role="tablist">					<li role="presentation" class="active"><a href="#about" aria-controls="about" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Course details</a></li>																		<li role="presentation"><a href="#transcript" aria-controls="transcript" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Transcript</a></li>														<li role="presentation"><a href="#pattern" aria-controls="pattern" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Pattern</a></li>					<li role="presentation"><a href="#diploma" aria-controls="transcript" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Diploma</a></li>						<li role="presentation"><a class="faq-tab blank" href="#faq" aria-controls="faq" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">FAQs</a></li>				  </ul>				  <!-- Tab panes -->				  <div class="tab-content">				  																									<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane active" id="about">											<div class="dark-get-started margin-0">																																											<p><strong><em>Dressmaker’s Treasury </em></strong><strong>is a collection of key tools and skills which every dressmaker needs for successful work. </strong></p><p><strong>I am offering you a great instrument to help you acquire more confidence for fulfilling your creative projects! </strong>You will no longer have any fear of complex sophisticated garments! You will learn to work with mock-ups, make crinolines of non-standard shapes, and sew various kinds of fabric cases for petticoats to enhance the fullness of the main skirt.</p><p><strong>Our main goal at the Corset Academy </strong>is to teach you how to sew wedding and evening garments. And I want you to be able to sew a high-quality garment within a relatively short time.</p><p><strong>I don’t want you to spend lots of time on doing complicated calculations and making basic skirt patterns! </strong></p><p><strong>All necessary materials are included in the course:</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><ul><li><h4>Patterns of four silhouette skirts in the actual size (PDF);</h4></li><li><h4>Patterns of four silhouette skirts in half the actual size for sewing mock-ups and designing new skirt models (PDF);</h4></li><li><h4>Three tables for AUTOMATIC calculation of all parameters required for cutting a trapeze-shaped skirt, a half-circle skirt, and a full-sweep skirt (HTML). These tables contain 18 tabs for calculating necessary parameters for the mentioned types of skirts, horizontal and vertical ruffles, falbalas, and the elastic waistband skirt.</h4></li><li><h4>Three tables for AUTOMATIC calculations with fixed parameters for the trapeze-shaped skirt, the half-circle skirt, and the full-sweep skirt (HTML);</h4></li></ul><h4>Fixed parameters (i.e. measurements) allow you to quickly calculate necessary data for cutting ruffles and falbalas for a skirt of a certain size: consumption of main fabric, lining fabric, decorative materials, etc.</h4><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Our new course&nbsp;<em>Dressmaker’s Treasury. Wedding Skirts and Petticoats </em>is a collection of important methods and skills which every dressmaker must know in order to achieve good results. It will be equally helpful for beginners and for experienced professionals! </strong></p><p><strong>Every professional dressmaker knows that sewing complex wedding skirts </strong>is not just about sewing together kilometers of fabric. The key thing is correct calculations and your ability to “foresee” the final results and related fabric consumption well before you start cutting and sewing.</p><p>I would also like to emphasize that the skirt from this course is merely a foundation for your own masterpieces. Let your creativity bloom!</p><p><strong>The course&nbsp;is&nbsp;useful both to beginner dressmakers, as well as experienced professionals.</strong></p><p><strong>Enjoy it!</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Author:</strong>&nbsp;Tatiana Kozorovitsky</p><p><strong>Total length:</strong>&nbsp;3h 31m</p>												</div>						</div>										<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="transcript">						<div class="overlay"></div>						<!-- BEGIN Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --><!-- Scope BEGIN: Article --><div itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Article"><!-- Scope BEGIN: Organization --><span itemprop="publisher" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Organization"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="logo" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="text" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="https://www.facebook.com/corsetacademy"></span> <!-- Scope END: Organization --><!-- Scope BEGIN: Person --><span itemprop="author" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Person"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tatiana Kozorovitsky"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="128"><meta itemprop="height" content="128"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/jpeg"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/author/infocorsetacademy-net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="http://www.corsetacademy.net"></span> <!-- Scope END: Person --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-9-sewing-a-mock-up-fishtail-skirt-with-separately-cut-bottom/"><meta itemprop="mainEntityOfPage" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-9-sewing-a-mock-up-fishtail-skirt-with-separately-cut-bottom/"><meta itemprop="datePublished" content="2018-05-04T16:52:36+00:00"><meta itemprop="dateModified" content="2018-05-07T18:46:25+00:00"><meta itemprop="copyrightYear" content="2018"><meta itemprop="inLanguage" content="en_US"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tutorial 9. Sewing a Mock-Up Fishtail Skirt with Separately Cut Bottom."><meta itemprop="headline" content="Tutorial 9. Sewing a Mock-Up Fishtail Skirt with Separately Cut Bottom."><meta itemprop="description" content="I have tried to classify them based on three main principles of constructing fishtail skirts with separately cut bottom part."><meta itemprop="articleSection" content="Wedding Skirts and Petticoats. Theoretical Part."><meta itemprop="keywords" content="wedding skirts and petticoats. theoretical part., video"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><div itemprop="articleBody"><h1>Tutorial 9. Sewing a Mock-Up Fishtail Skirt with Separately Cut Bottom.</h1><p><strong>There is a great variety of styles for skirts of this construction. </strong></p><p>I have tried to classify them based on three main principles of constructing fishtail skirts with separately cut bottom part.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%209.files/image002.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>1. Based on the type of the top part:</strong></p><p>- Straight skirt with standard darts;</p><p>- Skirt made of six gores.</p><p><strong>2. Based on the level of the horizontal joining seam: </strong></p><p>- Above knee-level;</p><p>- At knee-level;</p><p>- Below knee-level.</p><p><strong>3. Based on the incline of the joining seam: </strong></p><p>- The seam goes at an angle: ascending at the front and descending at the back;</p><p>- The seam goes in a horizontal line parallel to the floor;</p><p>- The seam goes at an angle: descending at the front and ascending at the back.</p><p><strong>I decided not to make a separate category for skirts with trains because the modeling process is the same regardless of whether the skirt is made with or without a train. </strong></p><p><strong>We haven’t discussed the shape of the separately cut falbala either yet. </strong></p><p><strong>Let us move to our skirts. </strong></p><p><strong>Everything is simple if we look at a soft silhouette dress without any inner supporting construction and with a horizontal seam joining the top with the bottom. </strong>The separately cut bottom part can have any configuration depending on the properties of fabric and the desired shape: it can be cut as a full-sweep skirt, a half-circle skirt, or a skirt with decorative gores. If you are sewing with thin fabrics, then the bottom part of the skirt may be made, for example, of four or five full-sweep skirts either sewn together into one piece or forming tiers.</p><p>I showed you how to put ruffles on the fishtail skirt to enhance the sloping shape of its bottom part <strong>back in the first edition of <em>Wedding Dresses </em>by the Corset Academy.</strong> My ruffles were thickly gathered strips of tulle put at 2cm intervals and reaching down to the very bottom of the skirt. This technique allows you to create a very full skirt with a very graceful silhouette. The same principle is used in the making of the popular elastic waist skirt.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%209.files/image004.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>But if the seam joining the top with the bottom is not horizontal, or if there is a stiff hoop construction underneath the skirt, then it is compulsory to sew a mock-up to avoid mistakes and achieve good results! </strong>Every skirt like that requires an individual approach which depends on many contributing factors. &nbsp;What are these factors? And how to use them to give the right shape to the bottom part of the skirt? We will talk about it in this tutorial.</p><p><strong>Although we will talk about petticoats in the tutorials to follow, we have to touch upon this subject now. </strong>Skirts and petticoats are inseparable topics − it is something you begin to understand gradually as you work with different styles of skirts and their inner supporting constructions.</p><p><strong>Let us start working on the shape of our fishtail skirt with complicated separately cut bottom part. </strong>We will need a petticoat and a mock-up skirt.</p><p><strong>I prefer using a standard petticoat with seven hoops for working with mock-ups. </strong>Its bottom hoop has a length of 280cm (140cm for our half-scale dress-form). It is equally perfect for designing a soft silhouette skirt or a classic fishtail skirt with an inner supporting construction.</p><p><strong>I put my half-scale petticoat on the half-scale dress-form. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%209.files/image006.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>We will talk about its pattern later. And now let me simply demonstrate how to use this petticoat in the making of a fishtail skirt with a separately cut bottom. </strong>Of course, it is possible that you will meet clients who will ask for a skirt with a bottom circumference of 350cm or even more than that. In that case, you will need to use a corresponding petticoat for working with the mock-up, but you can still follow the same instructions which I give you for the petticoat with a 280cm long bottom edge.</p><p><strong>Let me explain why I prefer this kind of a petticoat for skirts of this style. </strong>Judging from my experience, its bottom circumference is very convenient and very popular among brides: it is not too small and not too big. It is easy to walk in a skirt like this and, at the same time, it does not look too full (way too full skirts are notorious for making the wearer’s legs look short if she is of medium height). Simply put, a 280cm bottom circumference allows us to create a well-proportioned garment.</p><p><strong>Our mock-up is a skirt made of gores cut without flare and joined down to the supposed level of the falbala.</strong> The level of the joining seam is estimated very roughly. Do not make bar tacks when joining the gores at the top of the skirt so you can always undo the stitches.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%209.files/image008.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>The size of this skirt should be close to the size of your half-scale mock-up, but its circumference at the supposed level of the joining seam should not be smaller than your client’s Hip Circumference. </strong>Of course, you can adjust the pattern of the bottom part of the skirt by a couple of centimeters after polishing up the shape, but it is recommended to bring all adjustments down to a minimum.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%209.files/image010.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>I put the assembled mock-up on the dress-form with the petticoat. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%209.files/image012.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%209.files/image014.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>It is obvious that we don’t need the top hoops of the petticoat. I can safely remove them. </strong>It is for this reason that I prefer this petticoat with closely spaced seven hoops. I recommend you number all hoops so you can easily put them back in place later.</p><p><strong>I remove the top three hoops from the petticoat. </strong>The petticoat itself is pinned to the waist of the dress-form.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%209.files/image016.jpg" alt=""></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%209.files/image018.jpg" alt=""></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%209.files/image020.jpg" alt=""></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%209.files/image022.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>I can see that the skirt still does not fit the petticoat nicely even after I have removed those hoops. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%209.files/image024.jpg" alt=""></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%209.files/image026.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>I have to remove one more hoop. </strong>You must have already figured out my construction principle and why I need a petticoat with many hoops.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%209.files/image028.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>There are three bottom hoops left in the petticoat. As the result, the bottom part of the skirt resembles a balloon. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%209.files/image030.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>If you or your client don’t like this balloon shape, you can remove the fifth hoop. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%209.files/image032.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>The skirt will look different then. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%209.files/image034.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>As you can see, it is enough to leave two hoops at the bottom of the petticoat for our skirt which will feature a rather stiff inner construction made of a petticoat and stiff ruffles or multiple layers of fabric. </strong>You could also leave three hoops at the bottom. It would look beautiful with a full, voluminous skirt.</p><p><strong>The choice depends on the desired shape of the bottom part of the skirt. </strong></p><p><strong>If you want to sew a plain soft skirt with no stiff inner construction, then simply remove the one but last hoop and leave the very bottom hoop in the petticoat. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%209.files/image036.jpg" alt=""></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%209.files/image038.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>It may seem strange that I said the skirt would be soft with no inner construction but then left the bottom hoop there. </strong>In reality, the bottom hoop is only there to expand the separately cut bottom part of the skirt by the desired width. This separately cut falbala will simply sink down when not supported by the bottom hoop of the petticoat. Of course, a petticoat with only one hoop at the bottom cannot hold the beautiful shape of the skirt, but it will at least allow you to shape the gores in the desired way.</p><p><strong>I pin the mock-up skirt to the dress-form in the desired position. </strong>The side seams are aligned with those of the dress-form.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%209.files/image040.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>A spinning tray is a great tool for working with mock-ups. I got mine from IKEA. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%209.files/image042.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>I put the dress-form with the mock-up skirt on the tray and I can turn it left and right whenever I need. It is very convenient. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%209.files/image044.jpg" alt=""></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%209.files/image046.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>The skirt is secured in the right position. Please make sure to position the side seams and the central back seam of the petticoat correctly. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%209.files/image048.jpg" alt=""></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%209.files/image050.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>Do not be worried by the fact that the petticoat has shrunk and its shape has changed. This will not affect the process of modeling the skirt. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%209.files/image052.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>Our key goal at the moment is to determine the length of the skirt and the size of its gores considering the desired width of intervals between them. </strong></p><p>You can add some flare at this stage <strong>if you are making a soft silhouette skirt</strong>. Alternatively, you can do it later when working on the full-size garment.</p><p><strong>But if you are making a fishtail skirt with a stiff hoop,</strong> then the circumference of this hoop on the actual petticoat must strictly correspond with the circumference of the same hoop on the mock-up petticoat (only in full scale, of course).</p><p><strong>Experienced dressmakers know that you should always work on the petticoat before working on the skirt. </strong>First you sew a petticoat and then you start putting the skirt on it the way we are doing now. For this reason, working with our mock-up right now, we consider that we already have a matching petticoat with a 140cm long bottom hoop.</p><p><strong>There is a justified question: </strong>can’t I do the same work on a finished petticoat custom-made for the skirt? <strong>The answer is simple. </strong>I don’t have the skirt yet and so I cannot tell exactly how to sew a petticoat for it. One depends on the other. We need to find perfect balance to get a good skirt and a matching petticoat.</p><p><strong>And this is why it is compulsory to take all key measurements after finishing the mock-up skirt so we can use them for sewing the petticoat. </strong>The only strictly fixed value is the circumference of the bottom hoop – 140cm in half scale.</p><p><strong>Let us start working on the shape of the skirt. The separately cut part will go at an angle: it will be shorter at the front and longer at the back because of the train. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%209.files/image054.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>First of all, I rip the gore seams up to the level where the flare of the bottom part is supposed to begin.</strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%209.files/image056.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%209.files/image058.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>By the way, you can cut up the gores themselves at this stage </strong>to make an even more precise pattern. This depends on the complexity of the skirt itself and of the train. Please remember to keep controlling the level where the skirt is pinned to the dress-form to keep all adjustments symmetric and even.</p><p>I cut and sewed my mock-up skirt without the central back seam. But looking at it now, <strong>I feel like cutting the central piece of the bottom part in half. </strong>I want to visually make the train start higher. My technique makes it really easy to apply any adjustments missing in the basic mock-up construction. Everything is quite simple!</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%209.files/image060.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>I put my half-scale dress-form on the table and adjust its height </strong>so as to make the distance from the waist to the table correspond with the length of the skirt according to my client’s measurement. It is 110cm (55cm on the mock-up).</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%209.files/image062.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>It is also compulsory to measure the length of the skirt together with the petticoat. It is 56cm which corresponds with 112cm in the actual size. </strong>In other words, the flare makes the skirt a little longer.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%209.files/image064.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>And now let us move to one of the key moments in the whole process. We will start measuring the widths of gores which are to be inserted between the existing ones. </strong>You can pin strips of fabric to the existing gores to determine the widths of missing gores.</p><p><strong>Please note that different parts of the skirt have different amounts of flare. </strong></p><p><strong>Please look here and compare the flare at the front, at the sides, and at the back of the skirt.</strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%209.files/image066.jpg" alt=""></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%209.files/image068.jpg" alt=""></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%209.files/image070.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>It is another proof that the shape of the lining or the bottom supporting construction requires an individual approach. </strong>Every new skirt will have its own.</p><p><strong>And it is absolutely necessary to sew a mock-up for every new garment. </strong></p><p><strong>If your client brings you a picture with a dress of her dream, it will be very hard to guess how the base of the skirt is made even if it looks very similar to ours. </strong></p><p><strong>It would be wrong to assume </strong>that it is a half-circle skirt, a 2/3 circle skirt, or some other circle-based skirt.</p><p>It is impossible to guess the bottom circumference of the skirt <strong>just by looking at a picture of a garment </strong>because you don’t know the wearer’s height and you can’t estimate where exactly the flare begins.</p><p><strong>Various challenges and peculiarities will arise when you start sewing a similar garment for your client. </strong></p><p><strong>For example, </strong>the shape of the separately cut part depends largely on the type of face fabric. If it is thick, then you will want to make the face layer as close as possible to the shape of the base. If the face fabric is soft and thin, then you will want to create more folds. And there are lots of other contributing factors.</p><p><strong>It is why I keep insisting on sewing mock-ups for every new garment. You just cannot do without it! </strong></p><p><strong>I draw a line for the seam joining the top with the bottom on one half of the mock-up. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%209.files/image072.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>After drawing this line, I start moving apart the gores. </strong>I carefully spread them out and pin additional strips of fabric in place.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%209.files/image074.jpg" alt=""></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%209.files/image076.jpg" alt=""></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%209.files/image078.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>I pin additional strips of fabric to one half of the skirt, spread out the gores, and examine the shape of the garment. </strong>At this stage, you can clearly tell what width and shape the petticoat needs to have because you can already imagine the final results.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%209.files/image080.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>And now I need to draw a train. </strong>Skirts of such shape are typically made with a train. <strong>It is easy to draw one with the gores lying on the floor like that.</strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%209.files/image082.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>Now I have a full picture of how the train is supposed to pass over the side seam. </strong>I can see how to make a smooth graceful transition to the short part of the skirt, i.e. to its regular length to the floor.</p><p>Moreover, the mock-up method allows me to determine the precise length of the skirt in proportion with the circumference of the bottom petticoat hoop (280cm in full scale and 140cm in half scale).</p><p><strong>I trim the bottom edge of the skirt and double-check everything again to see whether the skirt fabric settles the way I wanted and the train looks beautiful. </strong></p><p><strong>This technique of working with half-scale mock-ups and dress-forms is extremely popular among all fashion designers! </strong></p><p><strong>It remains a mystery for me why few dressmakers who accept orders from private customers use half-scale dress-forms. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%209.files/image084.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>Now that we have polished up the silhouette of the skirt, we can make the line separating the bottom part from the top part more precise.</strong></p><p>It is also compulsory to draw the side seam and mark the positions of front midline, back midline, and princess seams.</p><p>And it is a good idea to mark additional points along the adjusted separating line for aligning the top part with the bottom part. These control points will be of great help later.</p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%209.files/image086.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>Now I can safely separate the bottom part of the skirt. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%209.files/image088.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>As the result, I have a proper mock-up of our skirt with separate top part and bottom part and with an even and precise joining line. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%209.files/image090.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>I lay the mock-up bottom part on the table to find the best way to divide it in gores. </strong>When the construction is simple enough, you can cut the piece along the side seam line and limit it to just two gores at the back and one gore with a fold line at the front. But if your skirt has a rather large train, then it makes sense to divide each back gore in half additionally. We will talk about it in detail in the next tutorial.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%209.files/image092.jpg" alt=""></p></div> <!-- Itemprop END: articleBody --></div> <!-- Scope END: Article --><!-- END Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --> 					</div>															<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="pattern">						<h3>Automatic&nbsp;Calculation Tables of All Parameters Required:</h3><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/sun/index.htm" target="_blank">Trapeze-Shaped Skirt</a></strong></p><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/halfSun/index.htm" target="_blank">Half-Circle Skirt</a></strong></p><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/dlina/index.htm" target="_blank">Full-Sweep Skirt</a> </strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><h3>Automatic&nbsp;Calculation&nbsp;Tables with Fixed Parameters:</h3><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/sunFix/index.htm" target="_blank">Trapeze-Shaped Skirt</a></strong></p><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/halfSunFix/index.htm" target="_blank">Half-Circle Skirt</a></strong></p><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/dlinaFix/index.htm" target="_blank">Full-Sweep Skirt</a></strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Sewing patterns are in PDF format.</p><p>To print sewing patterns open the files, press “print” and choose “<strong>PRINT IN ACTUAL SIZE</strong>“.</p><p>In each&nbsp;file the pattern is divided &nbsp;to A4 paper sheets for home printer.</p><h3>Skirt Patterns:</h3><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Patterns/flaredSkirt.pdf" target="_blank" class=""><img src="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset-rs/img/pdf.png"> Flared Skirt - Scale 1:2</a><br><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Patterns/flaredSkirtBig.pdf" target="_blank" class=""><img src="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset-rs/img/pdf.png"> Flared Skirt - Normal Size</a><br><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Patterns/skirtA.pdf" target="_blank" class=""><img src="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset-rs/img/pdf.png"> A-Line Skirt - Scale 1:2</a><br><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-w